[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] In mathematics, **approximation theory** is concerned with how functions can best be approximated with simpler functions, and with quantitatively characterizing the errors introduced thereby.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] What is meant by *best* and *simpler* will depend on the application.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] A closely related topic is the approximation of functions by generalized Fourier series, that is, approximations based upon summation of a series of terms based upon orthogonal polynomials.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] One problem of particular interest is that of approximating a function in a computer mathematical library, using operations that can be performed on the computer or calculator (e.g. addition and multiplication), such that the result is as close to the actual function as possible.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This is typically done with polynomial or rational (ratio of polynomials) approximations.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The objective is to make the approximation as close as possible to the actual function, typically with an accuracy close to that of the underlying computer's floating point arithmetic.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This is accomplished by using a polynomial of high degree, and/or narrowing the domain over which the polynomial has to approximate the function.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Narrowing the domain can often be done through the use of various addition or scaling formulas for the function being approximated.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Modern mathematical libraries often reduce the domain into many tiny segments and use a low-degree polynomial for each segment.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Once the domain (typically an interval) and degree of the polynomial are chosen, the polynomial itself is chosen in such a way as to minimize the worst-case error.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] That is, the goal is to minimize the maximum value of $\mid P(x)-f(x)\mid$ , where *P*(*x*) is the approximating polynomial, *f*(*x*) is the actual function, and *x* varies over the chosen interval.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] For well-behaved functions, there exists an *N*th-degree polynomial that will lead to an error curve that oscillates back and forth between $+\varepsilon$ and $-\varepsilon$ a total of *N*+2 times, giving a worst-case error of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] It is seen that there exists an *N*th-degree polynomial that can interpolate *N*+1 points in a curve.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] That such a polynomial is always optimal is asserted by the equioscillation theorem.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] It is possible to make contrived functions *f*(*x*) for which no such polynomial exists, but these occur rarely in practice.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] For example, the graphs shown to the right show the error in approximating log(x) and exp(x) for *N* = 4.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The red curves, for the optimal polynomial, are **level**, that is, they oscillate between $+\varepsilon$ and $-\varepsilon$ exactly.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] In each case, the number of extrema is *N*+2, that is, 6.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Two of the extrema are at the end points of the interval, at the left and right edges of the graphs.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] To prove this is true in general, suppose *P* is a polynomial of degree *N* having the property described, that is, it gives rise to an error function that has *N* + 2 extrema, of alternating signs and equal magnitudes.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The red graph to the right shows what this error function might look like for *N* = 4.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Suppose *Q*(*x*) (whose error function is shown in blue to the right) is another *N*-degree polynomial that is a better approximation to *f* than *P*.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This function changes sign at least *N*+1 times so, by the Intermediate value theorem, it has *N*+1 zeroes, which is impossible for a polynomial of degree *N*.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] One can obtain polynomials very close to the optimal one by expanding the given function in terms of Chebyshev polynomials and then cutting off the expansion at the desired degree.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This is similar to the Fourier analysis of the function, using the Chebyshev polynomials instead of the usual trigonometric functions.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] and then cuts off the series after the $T_{N}$ term, one gets an *N*th-degree polynomial approximating *f*(*x*).
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The reason this polynomial is nearly optimal is that, for functions with rapidly converging power series, if the series is cut off after some term, the total error arising from the cutoff is close to the first term after the cutoff.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] That is, the first term after the cutoff dominates all later terms.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The same is true if the expansion is in terms of bucking polynomials.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] If a Chebyshev expansion is cut off after $T_{N}$ , the error will take a form close to a multiple of $T_{N+1}$ .
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The Chebyshev polynomials have the property that they are level – they oscillate between +1 and −1 in the interval [−1, 1]. $T_{N+1}$ has *N*+2 level extrema.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This means that the error between *f*(*x*) and its Chebyshev expansion out to $T_{N}$ is close to a level function with *N*+2 extrema, so it is close to the optimal *N*th-degree polynomial.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] In the graphs above, the blue error function is sometimes better than (inside of) the red function, but sometimes worse, meaning that it is not quite the optimal polynomial.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The discrepancy is less serious for the exp function, which has an extremely rapidly converging power series, than for the log function.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Chebyshev approximation is the basis for Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature, a numerical integration technique.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The Remez algorithm (sometimes spelled Remes) is used to produce an optimal polynomial *P*(*x*) approximating a given function *f*(*x*) over a given interval.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] It is an iterative algorithm that converges to a polynomial that has an error function with *N*+2 level extrema.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] By the theorem above, that polynomial is optimal.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Remez's algorithm uses the fact that one can construct an *N*th-degree polynomial that leads to level and alternating error values, given *N*+2 test points.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] That means that the above equations are just *N*+2 linear equations in the *N*+2 variables $P_{0}$ , $P_{1}$ , ..., $P_{N}$ , and $\varepsilon$ .
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Given the test points $x_{1}$ , ..., $x_{N+2}$ , one can solve this system to get the polynomial *P* and the number $\varepsilon$ .
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The graph below shows an example of this, producing a fourth-degree polynomial approximating $e^{x}$ over [−1, 1].
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The error graph does indeed take on the values $\pm \varepsilon$ at the six test points, including the end points, but that those points are not extrema.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] If the four interior test points had been extrema (that is, the function *P*(*x*)*f*(*x*) had maxima or minima there), the polynomial would be optimal.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The second step of Remez's algorithm consists of moving the test points to the approximate locations where the error function had its actual local maxima or minima.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] For example, one can tell from looking at the graph that the point at −0.1 should have been at about −0.28.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The way to do this in the algorithm is to use a single round of Newton's method.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Since one knows the first and second derivatives of *P*(*x*) − *f*(*x*), one can calculate approximately how far a test point has to be moved so that the derivative will be zero.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Calculating the derivatives of a polynomial is straightforward.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] One must also be able to calculate the first and second derivatives of *f*(*x*).
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Remez's algorithm requires an ability to calculate $f(x)\,$ , $f'(x)\,$ , and $f''(x)\,$ to extremely high precision.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] The entire algorithm must be carried out to higher precision than the desired precision of the result.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] After moving the test points, the linear equation part is repeated, getting a new polynomial, and Newton's method is used again to move the test points again.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] This sequence is continued until the result converges to the desired accuracy.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Convergence is quadratic for well-behaved functions—if the test points are within $10^{-15}$ of the correct result, they will be approximately within $10^{-30}$ of the correct result after the next round.
[src:approximation-theory/approximation-theory] Remez's algorithm is typically started by choosing the extrema of the Chebyshev polynomial $T_{N+1}$ as the initial points, since the final error function will be similar to that polynomial.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, a **Bernstein polynomial** is a polynomial expressed as a linear combination of Bernstein basis polynomials.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The idea is named after mathematician Sergei Natanovich Bernstein.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Polynomials in this form were first used by Bernstein in a constructive proof of the Weierstrass approximation theorem.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] With the advent of computer graphics, Bernstein polynomials, restricted to the interval [0, 1], became important in the form of Bézier curves.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] A numerically stable way to evaluate polynomials in **Bernstein form** is de Casteljau's algorithm.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] where ${\tbinom {n}{\nu }}$ is a binomial coefficient.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The Bernstein basis polynomials of degree n form a basis for the vector space $\Pi _{n}$ of polynomials of degree at most n , all with real coefficients.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] is called a **Bernstein polynomial** or **polynomial in Bernstein form** of degree n .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The coefficients $\beta _{\nu }$ are called **Bernstein coefficients** or **Bézier coefficients**.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Let *ƒ* be a continuous function on the interval [0, 1].
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Bernstein polynomials thus provide one way to prove the Weierstrass approximation theorem that every real-valued continuous function on a real interval [*a*, *b*] can be uniformly approximated by polynomial functions over $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] is an eigenvalue of *B**n*; the corresponding eigenfunction is a polynomial of degree *k*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] This proof follows Bernstein's original proof of 1912.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] We will first give intuition for Bernstein's original proof.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] A continuous function on a compact interval must be uniformly continuous.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Thus, the value of any continuous function can be uniformly approximated by its value on some finite net of points in the interval.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] This consideration renders the approximation theorem intuitive, given that polynomials should be flexible enough to match (or nearly match) a finite number of pairs $(x,f(x))$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] To do so, we might (1) construct a function close to f on a lattice, and then (2) smooth out the function outside the lattice to make a polynomial.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The probabilistic proof below simply provides a constructive method to create a polynomial which is approximately equal to f on such a point lattice, given that "smoothing out" a function is not always trivial.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Taking the expectation of a random variable with a simple distribution is a common way to smooth.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Here, we take advantage of the fact that Bernstein polynomials look like Binomial expectations.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] We split the interval into a lattice of *n* discrete values.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Then, to evaluate any *f(x)*, we evaluate *f* at one of the *n* lattice points close to *x*, randomly chosen by the Binomial distribution.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The expectation of this approximation technique is polynomial, as it is the expectation of a function of a binomial RV.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The proof below illustrates that this achieves a uniform approximation of *f*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The crux of the proof is to (1) justify replacing an arbitrary point with a binomially chosen lattice point by concentration properties of a Binomial distribution, and (2) justify the inference from $x\approx X$ to $f(x)\approx f(X)$ by uniform continuity.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Suppose *K* is a random variable distributed as the number of successes in *n* independent Bernoulli trials with probability *x* of success on each trial; in other words, *K* has a binomial distribution with parameters *n* and *x*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Moreover, this relation holds uniformly in *x*, which can be seen from its proof via Chebyshev's inequality, taking into account that the variance of 1⁄*n* *K*, equal to 1⁄*n* *x*(1−*x*), is bounded from above by 1⁄(4*n*) irrespective of *x*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] uniformly in *x* for each $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] To justify this statement, we use a common method in probability theory to convert from closeness in probability to closeness in expectation.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] One splits the expectation of $\left|f\left({\frac {K}{n}}\right)-f\left(x\right)\right|$ into two parts split based on whether or not $\left|f\left({\frac {K}{n}}\right)-f\left(x\right)\right|<\epsilon$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] In the interval where the difference does not exceed *ε*, the expectation clearly cannot exceed *ε*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] In the other interval, the difference still cannot exceed 2*M*, where *M* is an upper bound for |*ƒ*(x)| (since uniformly continuous functions are bounded).
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] However, by our 'closeness in probability' statement, this interval cannot have probability greater than *ε*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Thus, this part of the expectation contributes no more than 2*M* times *ε*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Then the total expectation is no more than $\epsilon +2M\epsilon$ , which can be made arbitrarily small by choosing small *ε*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Finally, one observes that the absolute value of the difference between expectations never exceeds the expectation of the absolute value of the difference, a consequence of Hölder's Inequality.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Noting that our randomness was over *K* while *x* is constant, the expectation of *f(x)* is just equal to *f(x)*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] But then we have shown that $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} _{x}} f\left({\frac {K}{n}}\right)$ converges to *f(x)*.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Then we will be done if $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} _{x}} f\left({\frac {K}{n}}\right)$ is a polynomial in *x* (the subscript reminding us that *x* controls the distribution of *K*).
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] In the above proof, recall that convergence in each limit involving *f* depends on the uniform continuity of *f*, which implies a rate of convergence dependent on *f* 's modulus of continuity $\omega$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] It also depends on 'M', the absolute bound of the function, although this can be bypassed if one bounds $\omega$ and the interval size.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Thus, the approximation only holds uniformly across *x* for a fixed *f*, but one can readily extend the proof to uniformly approximate a set of functions with a set of Bernstein polynomials in the context of equicontinuity.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] and this equation can be applied twice to $t{\frac {d}{dt}}$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] The identities (1), (2), and (3) follow easily using the substitution $t=x/(1-x)$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Since *f* is uniformly continuous, given $\varepsilon >0$ , there is a $\delta >0$ such that $|f(a)-f(b)|<\varepsilon$ whenever $|a-b|<\delta$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Moreover, by continuity, $M=\sup |f|<\infty$ .
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] It follows that the polynomials *f**n* tend to *f* uniformly.
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] Bernstein polynomials can be generalized to *k* dimensions – the resulting polynomials have the form *B**i*1(*x*1) *B**i*2(*x*2) ...
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] In the simplest case only products of the unit interval [0,1] are considered; but, using affine transformations of the line, Bernstein polynomials can also be defined for products [*a*1, *b*1] × [*a*2, *b*2] × ... × [*a**k*, *b**k*].
[src:approximation-theory/bernstein-polynomial] is a straightforward extension of Bernstein's proof in one dimension.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] A **minimax approximation algorithm** (or **L∞ approximation** or **uniform approximation**) is a method to find an approximation of a mathematical function that minimizes maximum error.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] The Weierstrass approximation theorem states that every continuous function defined on a closed interval [a,b] can be uniformly approximated as closely as desired by a polynomial function.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] For practical work it is often desirable to minimize the maximum absolute or relative error of a polynomial fit for any given number of terms in an effort to reduce computational expense of repeated evaluation.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] Polynomial expansions such as the Taylor series expansion are often convenient for theoretical work but less useful for practical applications.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] Truncated Chebyshev series, however, closely approximate the minimax polynomial.
[src:approximation-theory/minimax-approximation-algorithm] One popular minimax approximation algorithm is the Remez algorithm.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In mathematical analysis, a **modulus of continuity** is a function ω : [0, ∞] → [0, ∞] used to measure quantitatively the uniform continuity of functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] for all *x* and *y* in the domain of *f*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Since moduli of continuity are required to be infinitesimal at 0, a function turns out to be uniformly continuous if and only if it admits a modulus of continuity.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Moreover, relevance to the notion is given by the fact that sets of functions sharing the same modulus of continuity are exactly equicontinuous families.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] For instance, the modulus ω(*t*) := *kt* describes the k-Lipschitz functions, the moduli ω(*t*) := *kt*α describe the Hölder continuity, the modulus ω(*t*) := *kt*(|log *t*|+1) describes the **almost Lipschitz** class, and so on.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In general, the role of ω is to fix some explicit functional dependence of ε on δ in the (ε, δ) definition of uniform continuity.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] The same notions generalize naturally to functions between metric spaces.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Moreover, a suitable local version of these notions allows to describe quantitatively the continuity at a point in terms of moduli of continuity.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] A special role is played by concave moduli of continuity, especially in connection with extension properties, and with approximation of uniformly continuous functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] For a function between metric spaces, it is equivalent to admit a modulus of continuity that is either concave, or subadditive, or uniformly continuous, or sublinear (in the sense of growth).
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Actually, the existence of such special moduli of continuity for a uniformly continuous function is always ensured whenever the domain is either a compact, or a convex subset of a normed space.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] are uniformly bounded for all pairs (*x*, *x*′) bounded away from the diagonal of *X x X*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] The functions with the latter property constitute a special subclass of the uniformly continuous functions, that in the following we refer to as the *special uniformly continuous* functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Real-valued special uniformly continuous functions on the metric space *X* can also be characterized as the set of all functions that are restrictions to *X* of uniformly continuous functions over any normed space isometrically containing *X*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Also, it can be characterized as the uniform closure of the Lipschitz functions on *X*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Moduli of continuity are mainly used to give a quantitative account both of the continuity at a point, and of the uniform continuity, for functions between metric spaces, according to the following definitions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] One equivalently says that ω is a modulus of continuity (resp., at *x*) for *f*, or shortly, *f* is ω-continuous (resp., at *x*).
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Here, we mainly treat the global notion.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Special moduli of continuity also reflect certain global properties of functions such as extendibility and uniform approximation.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In this section we mainly deal with moduli of continuity that are concave, or subadditive, or uniformly continuous, or sublinear.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Thus, for a function *f* between metric spaces it is equivalent to admit a modulus of continuity which is either concave, or subadditive, or uniformly continuous, or sublinear.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In this case, the function *f* is sometimes called a *special uniformly continuous* map.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] This is always true in case of either compact or convex domains.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Indeed, a uniformly continuous map *f* : *C* → *Y* defined on a convex set *C* of a normed space *E* always admits a subadditive modulus of continuity; in particular, real-valued as a function ω : [0, ∞) → [0, ∞).
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Note that as an immediate consequence, any uniformly continuous function on a convex subset of a normed space has a sublinear growth: there are constants *a* and *b* such that |*f*(*x*)| ≤ *a*|*x*|+*b* for all *x*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Conversely, at least for real-valued functions, any special uniformly continuous function is a bounded, uniformly continuous perturbation of some Lipschitz function; indeed more is true as shown below (Lipschitz approximation).
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] As remarked, any subadditive modulus of continuity is uniformly continuous: in fact, it admits itself as a modulus of continuity.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Therefore, *f*∗ and *f** are respectively inferior and superior envelopes of ω-continuous families; hence still ω-continuous.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Incidentally, by the Kuratowski embedding any metric space is isometric to a subset of a normed space.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Hence, special uniformly continuous real-valued functions are essentially the restrictions of uniformly continuous functions on normed spaces.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In particular, this construction provides a quick proof of the Tietze extension theorem on compact metric spaces.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] However, for mappings with values in more general Banach spaces than **R**, the situation is quite more complicated; the first non-trivial result in this direction is the Kirszbraun theorem.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Every special uniformly continuous real-valued function *f* : *X* → **R** defined on the metric space *X* is uniformly approximable by means of Lipschitz functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Moreover, the speed of convergence in terms of the Lipschitz constants of the approximations is strictly related to the modulus of continuity of *f*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] Since ω(*t*) = o(1) for *t* → 0+, it follows that δ(*s*) = o(1) for *s* → +∞, that exactly means that *f* is uniformly approximable by Lipschitz functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] in fact, it is the greatest *s*-Lipschitz function that realize the distance δ(*s*).
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] 160) attributes the first usage of omega for the modulus of continuity to Lebesgue (1909, p.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] 75) where omega refers to the oscillation of a Fourier transform.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] 7–8) mentions both names (1) "modulus of continuity" and (2) "modulus of oscillation" and then concludes "but we choose (1) to draw attention to the usage we will make of it".
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In other words, the map *h* → τ*h* defines a strongly continuous group of linear isometries of *Lp*.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] In the case *p* = ∞ the above property does not hold in general: actually, it exactly reduces to the uniform continuity, and defines the uniform continuous functions.
[src:approximation-theory/modulus-of-continuity] This way, moduli of continuity also give a quantitative account of the continuity property shared by all *Lp* functions.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] In mathematics, a **Padé approximant** is the "best" approximation of a function near a specific point by a rational function of given order.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Under this technique, the approximant's power series agrees with the power series of the function it is approximating.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The technique was developed around 1890 by Henri Padé, but goes back to Georg Frobenius, who introduced the idea and investigated the features of rational approximations of power series.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The Padé approximant often gives better approximation of the function than truncating its Taylor series, and it may still work where the Taylor series does not converge.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] For these reasons Padé approximants are used extensively in computer calculations.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] They have also been used as auxiliary functions in Diophantine approximation and transcendental number theory, though for sharp results, ad hoc methods—in some sense inspired by the Padé theory—typically replace them.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Since a Padé approximant is a rational function, an artificial singular point may occur as an approximation, but this can be avoided by Borel–Padé analysis.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The reason the Padé approximant tends to be a better approximation than a truncating Taylor series is clear from the viewpoint of the multi-point summation method.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Since there are many cases in which the asymptotic expansion at infinity becomes 0 or a constant, it can be interpreted as the "incomplete two-point Padé approximation", in which the ordinary Padé approximation improves on the method of truncating a Taylor series.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] When it exists, the Padé approximant is unique as a formal power series for the given *m* and *n*.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] One way to compute a Padé approximant is via the extended Euclidean algorithm for the polynomial greatest common divisor.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] For the [*m*/*n*] approximant, one thus carries out the extended Euclidean algorithm for $r_{0}=x^{m+n+1},\;r_{1}=T_{m+n}(x)$ and stops it at the last instant that $v_{k}$ has degree *n* or smaller.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Then the polynomials $P=r_{k},\;Q=v_{k}$ give the [*m*/*n*] Padé approximant.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] If one were to compute all steps of the extended greatest common divisor computation, one would obtain an anti-diagonal of the Padé table.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The zeta regularization value at *s* = 0 is taken to be the sum of the divergent series.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The functional equation for this Padé zeta function is $\sum _{j=0}^{n}a_{j}\zeta _{R}(s-j)=\sum _{j=0}^{m}b_{j}\zeta _{0}(s-j),$ where *aj* and *bj* are the coefficients in the Padé approximation.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The subscript '0' means that the Padé is of order [0/0] and hence, we have the Riemann zeta function.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Padé approximants can be used to extract critical points and exponents of functions.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] In thermodynamics, if a function *f*(*x*) behaves in a non-analytic way near a point *x* = *r* like $f(x)\sim |x-r|^{p}$ , one calls *x* = *r* a critical point and *p* the associated critical exponent of *f*.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] If sufficient terms of the series expansion of *f* are known, one can approximately extract the critical points and the critical exponents from respectively the poles and residues of the Padé approximants $[n/n+1]_{g}(x)$ , where $g=f'/f$ .
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] A Padé approximant approximates a function in one variable.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] An approximant in two variables is called a Chisholm approximant (after J.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Chisholm), in multiple variables a Canterbury approximant (after Graves-Morris at the University of Kent).
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] The conventional Padé approximation is determined to reproduce the Maclaurin expansion up to a given order.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Therefore, the approximation at the value apart from the expansion point may be poor.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] This is avoided by the 2-point Padé approximation, which is a type of multipoint summation method.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] By selecting the major behavior of $f_{0}(x),f_{\infty }(x)$ , approximate functions $F(x)$ such that simultaneously reproduce asymptotic behavior by developing the Padé approximation can be found in various cases.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] As a result, at the point $x\to \infty$ , where the accuracy of the approximation may be the worst in the ordinary Padé approximation, good accuracy of the 2-point Padé approximant is guaranteed.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Therefore, the 2-point Padé approximant can be a method that gives a good approximation globally for $x=0\sim \infty$ .
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] In cases where $f_{0}(x),f_{\infty }(x)$ are expressed by polynomials or series of negative powers, exponential function, logarithmic function or $x\ln x$ , we can apply 2-point Padé approximant to $f(x)$ .
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] There is a method of using this to give an approximate solution of a differential equation with high accuracy.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Also, for the nontrivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function, the first nontrivial zero can be estimated with some accuracy from the asymptotic behavior on the real axis.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] A further extension of the 2-point Padé approximant is the multi-point Padé approximant.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] This method treats singularity points $x=x_{j}(j=1,2,3,\dots ,N)$ of a function $f(x)$ which is to be approximated.
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] Besides the 2-point Padé approximant, which includes information at $x=0,x\to \infty$ , this method approximates to reduce the property of diverging at $x\sim x_{j}$ .
[src:approximation-theory/padé-approximant] As a result, since the information of the peculiarity of the function is captured, the approximation of a function $f(x)$ can be performed with higher accuracy.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The **Remez algorithm** or **Remez exchange algorithm**, published by Evgeny Yakovlevich Remez in 1934, is an iterative algorithm used to find simple approximations to functions, specifically, approximations by functions in a Chebyshev space that are the best in the uniform norm *L*∞ sense.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] It is sometimes referred to as **Remes algorithm** or **Reme algorithm**.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] A typical example of a Chebyshev space is the subspace of Chebyshev polynomials of order *n* in the space of real continuous functions on an interval, *C*[*a*, *b*].
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The polynomial of best approximation within a given subspace is defined to be the one that minimizes the maximum absolute difference between the polynomial and the function.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] In this case, the form of the solution is precised by the equioscillation theorem.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The Remez algorithm starts with the function f to be approximated and a set X of $n+2$ sample points $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n+2}$ in the approximation interval, usually the extrema of Chebyshev polynomial linearly mapped to the interval.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The result is called the polynomial of best approximation or the minimax approximation algorithm.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] A review of technicalities in implementing the Remez algorithm is given by W.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The Chebyshev nodes are a common choice for the initial approximation because of their role in the theory of polynomial interpolation.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Kilgore, Carl de Boor, and Allan Pinkus proved that there exists a unique *t**i* for each *L**n*, although not known explicitly for (ordinary) polynomials.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] This section provides more information on the steps outlined above.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] In this section, the index *i* runs from 0 to *n*+1.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] It should be clear that $(-1)^{i}E$ in this equation makes sense only if the nodes $x_{0},...,x_{n+1}$ are *ordered*, either strictly increasing or strictly decreasing.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Then this linear system has a unique solution.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] (As is well known, not every linear system has a solution.) Also, the solution can be obtained with only $O(n^{2})$ arithmetic operations while a standard solver from the library would take $O(n^{3})$ operations.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] To this end, use each time Newton's interpolation formula with the divided differences of order $0,...,n$ and $O(n^{2})$ arithmetic operations.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] This is the same as the equation above for $i=0,...,n$ and for any choice of *E*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] As mentioned above, the two terms in the denominator have same sign: *E* and thus $p(x)\equiv b_{0}+b_{1}x+\ldots +b_{n}x^{n}$ are always well-defined.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The equioscillation theorem states that under this condition no polynomial of degree *n* exists with error less than *E*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Indeed, if such a polynomial existed, call it ${\tilde {p}}(x)$ , then the difference $p(x)-{\tilde {p}}(x)=(p(x)-f(x))-({\tilde {p}}(x)-f(x))$ would still be positive/negative at the *n*+2 nodes $x_{i}$ and therefore have at least *n*+1 zeros which is impossible for a polynomial of degree *n*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Thus, this *E* is a lower bound for the minimum error which can be achieved with polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] In each P-region, the current node $x_{i}$ is replaced with the local maximizer ${\bar {x}}_{i}$ and in each N-region $x_{i}$ is replaced with the local minimizer.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] (Expect ${\bar {x}}_{0}$ at *A*, the ${\bar {x}}_{i}$ near $x_{i}$ , and ${\bar {x}}_{n+1}$ at *B*.) No high precision is required here, the standard *line search* with a couple of *quadratic fits* should suffice.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Each amplitude $|z_{i}|$ is greater than or equal to *E*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] The Theorem of *de La Vallée Poussin* and its proof also apply to $z_{0},...,z_{n+1}$ with $\min\{|z_{i}|\}\geq E$ as the new lower bound for the best error possible with polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Moreover, $\max\{|z_{i}|\}$ comes in handy as an obvious upper bound for that best possible error.
[src:approximation-theory/remez-algorithm] Some modifications of the algorithm are present on the literature.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] In mathematical analysis, the **Weierstrass approximation theorem** states that every continuous function defined on a closed interval [*a*, *b*] can be uniformly approximated as closely as desired by a polynomial function.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Because polynomials are among the simplest functions, and because computers can directly evaluate polynomials, this theorem has both practical and theoretical relevance, especially in polynomial interpolation.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The original version of this result was established by Karl Weierstrass in 1885 using the Weierstrass transform.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Stone considerably generalized the theorem and simplified the proof.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] His result is known as the **Stone–Weierstrass theorem**.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The Stone–Weierstrass theorem is a vital result in the study of the algebra of continuous functions on a compact Hausdorff space.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Further, there is a generalization of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem to noncompact Tychonoff spaces, namely, any continuous function on a Tychonoff space is approximated uniformly on compact sets by algebras of the type appearing in the Stone–Weierstrass theorem and described below.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] A different generalization of Weierstrass' original theorem is Mergelyan's theorem, which generalizes it to functions defined on certain subsets of the complex plane.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The page for Bernstein polynomials outlines a constructive proof of the above theorem.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Since C[*a*, *b*] is metrizable and separable it follows that C[*a*, *b*] has cardinality at most 2ℵ0.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The set C[*a*, *b*] of continuous real-valued functions on [*a*, *b*], together with the supremum norm ‖*f*‖ = sup*a* ≤ *x* ≤ *b* |*f* (*x*)| is a Banach algebra, (that is, an associative algebra and a Banach space such that ‖*fg*‖ ≤ ‖*f*‖·‖*g*‖ for all *f*, *g*).
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The set of all polynomial functions forms a subalgebra of C[*a*, *b*] (that is, a vector subspace of C[*a*, *b*] that is closed under multiplication of functions), and the content of the Weierstrass approximation theorem is that this subalgebra is dense in C[*a*, *b*].
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Stone starts with an arbitrary compact Hausdorff space X and considers the algebra C(*X*, **R**) of real-valued continuous functions on X, with the topology induced by the supremum norm.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] He wants to find subalgebras of C(*X*, **R**) which are dense.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] It turns out that the crucial property that a subalgebra must satisfy is that it *separates points*: a set A of functions defined on X is said to separate points if, for every two different points x and y in X there exists a function p in A with *p*(*x*) ≠ *p*(*y*).
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] This implies Weierstrass' original statement since the polynomials on [*a*, *b*] form a subalgebra of C[*a*, *b*] which contains the constants and separates points.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] A version of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem is also true when X is only locally compact.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Let C0(*X*, **R**) be the space of real-valued continuous functions on X that vanish at infinity; that is, a continuous function *f* is in C0(*X*, **R**) if, for every *ε* > 0, there exists a compact set *K* ⊂ *X* such that |*f*| < *ε* on *X* \ *K*.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Again, C0(*X*, **R**) is a Banach algebra with the supremum norm.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] A subalgebra A of C0(*X*, **R**) is said to **vanish nowhere** if not all of the elements of A simultaneously vanish at a point; that is, for every x in X, there is some *f* in A such that *f* (*x*) ≠ 0.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] This version clearly implies the previous version in the case when X is compact, since in that case C0(*X*, **R**) = C(*X*, **R**).
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] There are also more general versions of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem that weaken the assumption of local compactness.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The Stone–Weierstrass theorem can be used to prove the following two statements, which go beyond Weierstrass's result.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Slightly more general is the following theorem, where we consider the algebra $C(X,\mathbb {C} )$ of complex-valued continuous functions on the compact space X , again with the topology of uniform convergence.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] This is a C*-algebra with the *-operation given by pointwise complex conjugation.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The complex unital *-algebra generated by S consists of all those functions that can be obtained from the elements of S by throwing in the constant function 1 and adding them, multiplying them, conjugating them, or multiplying them with complex scalars, and repeating finitely many times.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] As in the real case, an analog of this theorem is true for locally compact Hausdorff spaces.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The following is an application of this complex version.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Following Holladay (1957), consider the algebra C(*X*, **H**) of quaternion-valued continuous functions on the compact space X, again with the topology of uniform convergence.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The space of complex-valued continuous functions on a compact Hausdorff space X i.e. $C(X,\mathbb {C} )$ is the canonical example of a unital commutative C*-algebra ${\mathfrak {A}}$ .
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The space *X* may be viewed as the space of pure states on ${\mathfrak {A}}$ , with the weak-* topology.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] In 1960, Jim Glimm proved a weaker version of the above conjecture.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Stone's original proof of the theorem used the idea of lattices in C(*X*, **R**).
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] A subset L of C(*X*, **R**) is called a lattice if for any two elements *f*, *g* ∈ *L*, the functions max{ *f*, *g*}, min{ *f*, *g*} also belong to L.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] The above versions of Stone–Weierstrass can be proven from this version once one realizes that the lattice property can also be formulated using the absolute value | *f* | which in turn can be approximated by polynomials in *f* .
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Another generalization of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem is due to Errett Bishop.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Glicksberg (1962) gives a short proof of Bishop's theorem using the Krein–Milman theorem in an essential way, as well as the Hahn–Banach theorem: the process of Louis de Branges (1959).
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] Nachbin's theorem gives an analog for Stone–Weierstrass theorem for algebras of complex valued smooth functions on a smooth manifold.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] In 1885 it was also published in an English version of the paper whose title was *On the possibility of giving an analytic representation to an arbitrary function of real variable*.
[src:approximation-theory/weierstrass-approximation-theorem] According to the mathematician Yamilet Quintana, Weierstrass "suspected that any analytic functions could be represented by power series".
